segments.text: I can give you many examples of that.
Venezuelan equine encephalomyelitis entered the state of Texas in July of 1971.
We had no expertise in that disease.
I see.
Whole cholera entered Texas in that same year from Mexico.
Whole cholera is now a foreign animal disease.
Exotic Newcastle disease has been diagnosed in Texas in poultry.
Screw worms.
Some of these diseases are not necessarily tropical diseases, but diseases that are foreign to this country and diseases in which a tremendous expertise should be developed in order to cope with them
Before they hit, not after.
We were caught with our pants down when VWE hit Texas.
Which is what, VWE?
Venezuelan equine cephalomyelitis.
And if it hadn't been for the vaccine that had been developed by the Army at Fort Detrick, we would have been up the proverbial creek.
So, in your opinion then, would you say, and I don't want to put words in your mouth, but would you say that this college and their research seems to be short-sighted?
Well, Dr. Anderson, I think the reason- Or just too narrow and- No, the reason why the research isn't broader than it is is I think
because all animal disease research now, practically all animal disease research is controlled through the Experiment Station.
I think it should be the responsibility of the College of Veterinary Medicine to do animal disease research.
The expertise for animal disease research resides in the College of Animal Medicine, not in the Experiment Station.
And the present setup, whereby the director of the Experiment Station controlled the monies to fund animal disease research, I don't think
is advantageous for the College of Veterinary Medicine.
This is a political, infrastructural policy over which I exercise absolutely no say.
But in my opinion, the College of Veterinary Medicine should be the sole agent for the university system in matters pertaining to animal disease research.
This is not to say that some research should not be done collaboratively with the departments of animal science, entomology, or any other department.
For example, in fish culture, mariculture study, we ought to cooperate with other departments on this campus in...
in bringing the best minds of the university system to bear upon a problem.
That's my opinion.
In other words, it seems that we need more cooperation and coordination of our research efforts?
I think that one of the things that is necessary is that the College of Veterinary Medicine be given more autonomy.
There is no reason in the world why a research project that is written by a veterinary researcher ought to be approved by the experiment station.
I think that's absurd.
It should be approved by the dean here and then by the president of the university.
I don't see any reason why we should respond to an intermediate agency
that has no expertise in animal health, except the director.
And the director is a veterinarian who had never functioned as a veterinarian for the last 20 years of his life.
He's been an administrator.
But you see, he used to be associate dean for research here before his promotion.
But in my opinion, there isn't the fluidity

of administrative matters that should circulate between this college and the Office of International Programs, for example, I think there should be more intimate contact between the Office of International Programs and the College of Veterinary Medicine in matters pertaining to animal health.
I'm not talking about
academic matters.
I'm not talking about the possible recruitment of foreign students to the College of Veterinary Medicine.
That's not what I'm talking about.
I'm talking about capitalizing on opportunities that exist abroad for the research of animal diseases that could possibly threaten
the welfare of this state and of this country.
Let me give you an example.
African swine fever is a deadly disease of swine for which there is no vaccine.
Traditionally, African swine fever has been limited to Africa and to Spain and Portugal and other countries in that area of the world.
But in 1978, this disease broke out in Brazil.
From Brazil, it has spread to Dominican Republic, it has spread to Haiti, and it's now in Cuba.
And it is too close for comfort.
If it hits the United States, and I am convinced that it will enter the United States.
I don't know when, but I think it will hit this country.
And I think that this College of Veterinary Medicine ought to be readying
for the time when this disease is going to hit our shores.
And right now, there has been, for the last few years, a limitation of funds from the federal government for animal disease research.
But what little monies there have come to the university, they have gone to the experiment station.
Of course, the director of the experiment station has complete latitude to determine where that money should go.
What agency in the country would be working on this African?

Well, right now, for example, to answer your question, the United States Department of Agriculture is cooperating with the Food and Agricultural Organization of the United Nations to fund a team of people that is established in Santo Domingo, the Dominican Republic,
to transfer the technology necessary for those people who diagnose African Swine Fever, and not only them, but also all the Caribbean countries and South and Central American countries.
This university possesses the personnel that are qualified to head up that program, and I think international programs
could very easily be the focal point from which a proposal could be turned into FAO and say, let Texas A&M provide the personnel and here's how much it would cost.
They're looking for personnel right now, but it is, I think, there's been a discouragement of participation in
in the international animal health problem.
And here in our administration?
In our own college, in our own university.
Why do you think that is?
Well, maybe because of the well-tried Texas axiom, you know, that what happens in other countries is no business of ours.
We've got enough animal health problems in our own state
we should direct our efforts to the solution of those and to hell with everybody else.
I think that's the reason.
Although I doubt very much that you would find anybody on this campus that would admit to that.
That's the result.
Also, if you disagree with existing policy and you try and point to people and say,
We have to develop some knowledge about this disease.
We can do it on foreign soil where it will not be a threat to Texas.
We can make a significant contribution in this area by developing a vaccine against African swine fever or against babesiosis or against anaplasmosis.
We have the opportunity to dispatch our people to foreign soil and let them

set up a laboratory that that will work and address these problems without endangering our own uh situation at home and won't cost the state of Texas anything but you try and get these people to to uh to encourage that that type of thinking and they look the other way and they're the ones that are in charge of these decisions i've been very very disillusioned by by the
by the morale that had been affected adversely here among people who are in this College of Veterinary Medicine.

There are a lot of veterinarians who would like to do some research abroad, but there is no room under the present policy for this to happen, and it is not likely to change until the only way you can do that is to
is to emulate the program in other universities.
How do they respond?
Why should $125,000 go to the University of Tennessee, who has yet to graduate its first student for agricultural research, when the state of Texas A&M has been here since 1876?
in the School of Veterinary Medicine since 1916.
Why should a university who is unproved in this field get $125,000 from a private industrial giant?
Tennessee did.
Tennessee did?
Yeah.
$125,000 of gift from the International Chemical and Mineral Corporation for research in
in agricultural research, primarily with a tropical flavor, you know.
There's no reason in the world why that money should not be here, because this College of Veterinary Medicine has more expertise in foreign animal diseases.
It has the diagnostic laboratory here very, very, very close by.
It has people who have served abroad and who want to serve abroad, but then if they serve abroad, they'll get out of the tenure track.
Really?
Sure.
There's another point that I tried to sell.
Why should a guy who was assigned as a member of the A&M teaching faculty abroad
lose his opportunity to earn tenure.
That doesn't make sense to me.
If you consider him good enough to hire and respond to a contract and be classified as a member of the A&M team abroad, you should also consider him worthy of earning tenure.
But he has no academic rank as long as he's abroad, you see.
Unless he earned that academic rank before,
he was dispatched abroad.
So it sort of discriminates against a person who is interested in international education?
I think so.
I think so.
I certainly have not elaborated any more proposals.
I wrote dozens of proposals when I was director of the experiment, director of the Institute of Tropical Veterinary Medicine.
And it so happened that my directorship
coincided with the with the lowest awards in international veterinary medicine that this country had experienced.
It's a very complex topic because you see AID, the Agency for International Development was instrumental in
in organizing a method by which funds for international research could be apportioned to deserving universities.
And they appointed a board that is called the Board of International Food and Agricultural Development.
They appointed a committee that's called the Joint Committee for Agricultural Research.
And another committee, and this is under the Title 12 program,
And the Title 12 program for two and a half years had not been well organized enough to make these awards expeditiously.
They had spent too much time organizing themselves.
As a matter of fact, our own President Miller is a member of one of those committees, the Joint Committee for Agricultural Development.
Well, what I'm telling you is that if this university manifested a sincere effort to participate in international agricultural projects, that it could do so.
We have, and particularly, an international animal health problem.
We have the expertise.
We have the willingness.
and we have personnel who wish to be assigned abroad, but their economic stability cannot be guaranteed by assignment to one of these international projects.
I have made no effort now because I hadI'm silent now in this area.
I don't intend to
to aggravate anybody else.
I have done enough of that for the last four years.
It is clear that they have not moved in that direction, and so it's useless for me to keep on fighting, and I must address my own interest, and that is to teach pathology.
Okay, I have one final but large question to ask.
Now, you left in 1959 and came back in 1975.
What were the changes that you noticed when you got back?
Changes in the College of Vet Medicine?
Well, many changes.
You know, when I left here, there were 32 people on the faculty.
I would venture that today there's 140 on the teaching staff here, without counting them.
That's my guess.
That's a tremendous change.
Whereas we used to accept only 64 a year, now they're taking 145 or so candidates.
And the growth has been phenomenal.
not only in the College of Environmental Medicine, but university-wide.
The construction of new buildings, the monies that this university has attracted for research purposes.
We have some very, very outstanding scientists in other fields, such as nuclear physics, and such as
in marine sciences.
To answer your question, the primary changes that I have seen have been of phenomenal growth that would blow anybody's mind.
Women students also.
Yes, of course.
When I was on the faculty here, every year they would take a poll among the faculty to find out whether we would support a coeducational university.
Oh, really?
Back in the 1950s?
Yes, sir.
Every year I voted in favor of it.
Because there again, you see, the traditionalists were acting as an anchor around A&M's neck.
They didn't want to admit any women.
you know, to say that this is a provincial attitude is to utter a gross understatement.
And the mentality of a lot of otherwise good Aggies who think that by preserving the traditions of A&M and all that, that they're going to
to function in the best interest of the university.
That's a fallacy that no one can impress them with adequately.
Not even by hitting them across the forehead with a 4x4.
We could see that in the 50s when this university was losing enrollment to the other Southwest Conference schools.
Our enrollment was really falling.
because the kids didn't want to come here if there were no girls here.
And another thing is that it's just immoral to deny admission to a woman simply because for the previous 75 years no woman had attended.
You know, there's no reason.
It was the final awakening and the realization when they started hitting A&M in the pocketbook that we were not going to attract
deserving human beings to this university, in teaching, research, or in the student body, unless we changed our thinking.
And it was that economic stress and the possibility of aggravating a bad economic state that caused A&M to change.
And fortunately, we had a president here whose vision was unlimited, and that was Earl Rutter.
and it was, it was, it was his vision and his leadership that embarked A&M upon a program of phenomenal growth, I think.
Now how did, how did your colleagues back in the 1950s vote?
Was it a pretty close vote about women, or?
The faculty always overwhelmingly voted in favor of co-educational university.
In the College of Medicine?
Those that I knew.
I really believe that this was the case among the faculty in the other departments as well.
Oh yeah, it was.
It was.
But it was the student body and the alumni who were the unshakable traditionalists that kept A&M from being co-educational for so many years.
And then finally there was a suit brought against A&M by women who wanted to attend the College of Animal Medicine.
This is the only school in the state.
They wouldn't have to go to court if people had the foresight, you know, to see that this was immoral.
And it was this federal suit that was brought against A&M for this purpose that finally
began to change a lot of people's minds.
Yeah, this is the only land grant institution in the entire nation that was all male.
There's no rhyme or reason for that, to that, but see there's a mentality among, among, among people in Texas that
is difficult to put your finger on and say, this guy is going to think this way or going to react this way towards minorities or towards women or towards the possible benefits of expansion.
There's a lot of people who even now today say that the worst thing that could have happened to A&M was for A&M to grow as rapidly as it did.

we are going to pay the penalty for because we're not prepared for this phenomenal growth and we're going to be playing catch up and all but the statistics don't seem to support that that kind of thing we continue to draw tremendous sums of money for research I think that we we are at the latest count that I heard we were about number 17 in the country
in the amount of research dollars that are poured into this country, into this university.
It merits it.
We genuinely have, I think, the best university in this country.
It could be made better.
We should not rest on our past laurels.
Why do you think it's the best university in the country?
Because of many reasons.
Its location,
because of the tremendous influence of agriculture on our state.
And this is primarily an agricultural university.
It has the biggest college of agriculture in the country.
People come to A&M to learn about how to be better ranchers, better farmers, and better stockmen.
better swine producers, or better poultry producers, or in horticulture, how to produce more fruit out of orchards, how to make use of our tremendous resources in the state.
You know, our citrus industry could be improved greatly, and I think it would really compete with Florida and California if, you know, if the marketing

difficulties could be worked out we can produce better grapefruit than Florida can our soil is better this this state is gifted with a tremendous number of resources not the least of which is oil but also a tremendous capacity to produce agriculturally and because of the experience and
and the contributions that have been made by so many outstanding people.
People in the animal science are doing incredible things in conjunction with our own veterinarians.
They have, they have done a lot to increase the productivity of the state in agriculture.
Okay, I'm gonna ask you one last question.
All right.
asked before, how would you summarize your contribution to the College of Veterinary Medicine?
Well, I think that probably I rank my establishment of all three laboratories as my outstanding contribution to this university.
In other words, the Institute of Tropical Veterinary Medicine had been in existence

for 12 years, and it didn't have a place to really do some outstanding research at Falcon Heights, in an area that is owned by the U.S. Department of Agriculture, and an area in which they have allowed us to work jointly with them.
I established the laboratory, the Arthropod Tissue Culture Lab,
thinking that by growing tick cell lines, we might be able to make a vaccine against Texas fever.
Now, that's not, that work is still going on.
We are the only laboratory in the Western Hemisphere that has grown those ticks in culture, adapted those cells to culture.
And I think that those are probably my, my greatest contributions.
I have taught over 300 veterinarians in the state of Texas.
I think that that's also a contribution that I made to my profession here in the state.
The head of my department was my student.
Really?
That's right, Dr. Pierce.
The head of the physiology and pharmacology department was my student, Dr. McCready.
I still have several of my students here.
Dr. Crawford in public health was my student.
Dr. Huff, Dr. Kleber, these guys were all students of mine.
The present president of the Texas Veterinary Medical Association is the next student of mine.
So I think that in these areas where I have helped to shape the destiny of some of our students, those are the ways in which I have contributed.
Well, that's a good way to end the interview.
Thank you very much.
